# .env.example

```
# Server Configuration
PORT=4000
NODE_ENV=development

# Database Configuration
DB_HOST=localhost
DB_PORT=27017
DB_NAME=michael_gruen_db
DB_USER=
DB_PASS=

# Authentication
JWT_SECRET=your_jwt_secret
JWT_EXPIRATION=3600

# Email Configuration
EMAIL_HOST=smtp.example.com
EMAIL_PORT=587
EMAIL_USER=example@example.com
EMAIL_PASS=your_email_password

# Payment Gateway Configuration
STRIPE_API_KEY=your_stripe_api_key

# Social Media API Keys
TWITTER_API_KEY=your_twitter_api_key
INSTAGRAM_API_KEY=your_instagram_api_key
FACEBOOK_API_KEY=your_facebook_api_key

# Analytics
GOOGLE_ANALYTICS_TRACKING_ID=your_google_analytics_tracking_id

# External API Configuration
EXTERNAL_API_URL=https://api.external-service.com
EXTERNAL_API_KEY=your_external_api_key

# Security
SSL_CERT_PATH=/path/to/ssl/cert.pem
SSL_KEY_PATH=/path/to/ssl/key.pem

# Cloud Hosting Provider
CLOUD_PROVIDER=AWS
CLOUD_API_KEY=your_cloud_provider_api_key
CLOUD_API_SECRET=your_cloud_provider_api_secret

# Miscellaneous
SITE_DOMAIN=www.michaelgruen.com
ADMIN_EMAIL=admin@michaelgruen.com
SUPPORT_EMAIL=support@michaelgruen.com
```

This `.env.example` file provides a template for setting up environment variables required for the application. It includes placeholders for server configuration, database credentials, authentication secrets, email server details, payment gateway API keys, social media API keys, analytics tracking ID, external API configurations, security certificate paths, cloud hosting provider credentials, and miscellaneous settings. Users should create their own `.env` file based on this template and fill in the actual values for their environment.